dict.string: BBEdit uses Apple Events to interact with external tools such as Xcode and file transfer clients. BBEdit also sends itself Apple Events to implement many of its own features.

BBEdit may read files that are in your Desktop folder during normal usage. This includes files that were previously left open, as well as files that are aliased from one of its menu folders (such as Scripts, Clippings, or Text Filters).

BBEdit may read files that are in your Documents folder during normal usage. This includes files that were previously left open, as well as files that are aliased from one of its menu folders (such as Scripts, Clippings, or Text Filters).

BBEdit may read files that are in your Downloads folder during normal usage. This includes files that were previously left open, as well as files that are aliased from one of its menu folders (such as Scripts, Clippings, or Text Filters).

BBEdit may read files that are on network volumes during normal usage. This includes files that were previously left open, as well as files that are aliased from one of its menu folders (such as Scripts, Clippings, or Text Filters).

BBEdit may read files that are on removable disks during normal usage. This includes files that were previously left open, as well as files that are aliased from one of its menu folders (such as Scripts, Clippings, or Text Filters).
